 <p>I'm working on an application that uses lancedb's Rust crate for storage. I'm saving dates as unix integers, but LanceDB formats them as iso strings with a trailing decimal... sometimes.</p>
<pre class="lang-bash prettyprint-override"><code>Last Read: &quot;1970-01-01T00:00:00&quot;
Date Error: ParseError(NotEnough)
Last Read: &quot;2025-08-02T17:35:41.409&quot;
Date Error: ParseError(NotEnough)
Last Read: &quot;2025-08-04T01:48:44.017&quot;
Date Error: ParseError(NotEnough)
Last Read: &quot;2025-08-04T23:02:20.584&quot;
Date Error: ParseError(NotEnough)
Last Read: &quot;2025-08-05T00:08:57.350&quot;
Date Error: ParseError(NotEnough)
Last Read: &quot;2025-08-10T18:31:26.628&quot;
</code></pre>
<p>How can I reliably read dates from the database and convert them back into an integer, or at least to a <code>chrono::DateTime</code> struct?</p>
<p>Right now, the function attempting to parse the date string returned in the format above is:</p>
<pre class="lang-rs prettyprint-override"><code>pub fn date_string_to_int(d: &amp;str) -&gt; FlusterResult&lt;i64&gt; {
    let format = &quot;%Y-%m-%dT%T%.f&quot;;
    let date_time = chrono::DateTime::parse_from_str(d, format).map_err(|e| {
        println!(&quot;Date Error: {:?}&quot;, e);
        FlusterError::FailToParseDate
    })?;
    println!(&quot;Datetime: {:?}&quot;, date_time);
    Ok(0)
}
</code></pre>
<p>Any help is greatly appreciated.</p>


